															<img loading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"1024" heig=
ht=3D"415" src=3D"https://boxplotcalculator.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/=
box_plot-1024x415.webp" class=3D"attachment-large size-large wp-image-392" =
alt=3D"Box and whisker plot showing minimum, first quartile, median, third =
quartile, and maximum values with mean highlighted." title=3D"Box Plot Calc=
ulator Example - Box Plot Calculator">															</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-d238eed elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"d238eed" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p style=3D"text-align: center;"><em>Figure 1: Example box and whi=
sker plot created by the Box Plot Calculator.</em></p>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-103daef0 elementor-wi=
dget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"103daef0" data-element_type=
=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p><strong data-start=3D"2236" data-end=3D"2258">4. Reset (if need=
ed):</strong> If you want to analyse a new dataset, you can click the <stro=
ng data-start=3D"2313" data-end=3D"2324">=E2=80=9CReset=E2=80=9D</strong> b=
utton to clear the previous data and results. Then, input a new set of numb=
ers and recalculate.</p>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-318380b9 elementor-wi=
dget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"318380b9" data-element_type=
=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p>By following these steps, you can quickly generate a box plot a=
nd summary for any dataset. The interface is user-friendly: enter your numb=
ers and let the tool do the heavy lifting, computing the statistics and plo=
tting the graph.</p>								</div>
				</div>
				</div>
		<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-773acb61 e-con-full e-f=
lex e-con e-child" data-id=3D"773acb61" data-element_type=3D"container" id=
=3D"definition">
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-24bde2a elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-heading" data-id=3D"24bde2a" data-element_type=3D"widg=
et" data-widget_type=3D"heading.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
					<span id=3D"elementor-toc__heading-anchor-6" class=3D"elementor-menu-a=
nchor "></span><h2 class=3D"elementor-heading-title elementor-size-default"=
>What is a Box Plot?</h2>				</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-581aab3e elementor-wi=
dget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"581aab3e" data-element_type=
=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p>A <strong data-start=3D"16904" data-end=3D"16916">box plot</str=
ong> (also known as a <strong data-start=3D"16934" data-end=3D"16958">box-a=
nd-whisker plot</strong>) is a <strong data-start=3D"16965" data-end=3D"170=
09">graphical tool in descriptive statistics</strong> that provides a visua=
l summary of a dataset based on its quartiles. In simple terms, a box plot =
uses a box and lines (whiskers) to show the distribution of a set of number=
s. It highlights where the majority of values lie and identifies values tha=
t are significantly higher or lower than the rest (the outliers)=E2=80=8B</=
p>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-7e906b39 elementor-wi=
dget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"7e906b39" data-element_type=
=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p>In a box plot, the data is summarised by five key values =E2=80=
=93 the minimum, first quartile, median, third quartile, and maximum, which=
, as we discussed, make up the <strong data-start=3D"17569" data-end=3D"175=
92">five-number summary</strong>. These five points are plotted on a number=
 line and then enclosed in a box (for Q1 to Q3) with whiskers extending to =
the minimum and maximum values. This creates a picture of the data=E2=80=99=
s range and variability. Because it displays the middle 50% of the data as =
a box, you can quickly see where the central concentration of the data lies=
. Any points outside the whiskers are =E2=80=9Cthose <strong data-start=3D"=
18001" data-end=3D"18013">outliers</strong> that =E2=80=9Cgreatly =E2=80=9C=
differ from the norm.</p>								</div>
				</div>
				</div>
		<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-2c3139f e-con-full e-fl=
ex e-con e-child" data-id=3D"2c3139f" data-element_type=3D"container" id=3D=
"whisker">
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-b81ca46 elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-heading" data-id=3D"b81ca46" data-element_type=3D"widg=
et" data-widget_type=3D"heading.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
					<span id=3D"elementor-toc__heading-anchor-7" class=3D"elementor-menu-a=
nchor "></span><h2 class=3D"elementor-heading-title elementor-size-default"=
>The Box-and-Whisker Plot Visualization</h2>				</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-2a8b177 elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"2a8b177" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p>Alongside the numerical output, the Box Plot Calculator generat=
es a <strong data-start=3D"8530" data-end=3D"8554">box-and-whisker plot</st=
rong> =E2=80=94 a graphical representation of your data=E2=80=99s distribut=
ion using the five-number summary. This plot is the namesake of the tool an=
d provides an immediate visual summary. Below, we describe the components o=
f the box plot and how to read it.</p>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-50ae604 elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-image" data-id=3D"50ae604" data-element_type=3D"widget=
" data-widget_type=3D"image.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
															<img decoding=3D"async" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/=
wikipedia/commons/e/ed/Box_Plot_Picture.png" title=3D"" alt=3D"Image displa=
ying Box Plot" loading=3D"lazy">															</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-5d3ba59 elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"5d3ba59" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p><em data-start=3D"8834" data-end=3D"9423">Figure: Example of a =
box-and-whisker plot for an example dataset (shown in orange). The left whi=
sker end marks the minimum value (2), and the right whisker end marks the m=
aximum value (15). The central box spans from the first quartile (Q1 =3D 3.=
5) to the third quartile (Q3 =3D 9.6), and the vertical line inside the box=
 is at the median (6.1). This visual layout makes it easy to see where the =
middle 50% of the data lies (within the box) and the overall range of the d=
ata, from minimum to maximum. In this example, no data points lie beyond th=
e whiskers, indicating no outliers by the 1.5=C3=97IQR rule.</em></p>						=
		</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-960d69c elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"960d69c" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p>Each part of the box plot corresponds to part of the five-numbe=
r summary:</p>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-6ff0a15 elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"6ff0a15" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<ul><li><strong data-start=3D"9502" data-end=3D"9514">The Box:</st=
rong> This is the rectangle drawn from Q1 (bottom of the box) to Q3 (top of=
 the box). It represents the middle 50% of the data (the interquartile rang=
e). The height of the box (if the plot is vertical) or the width of the box=
 (if the plot is horizontal) equals the IQ. Data points inside this box are=
 considered the =E2=80=9Cmiddle=E2=80=9D cluster of values. A taller box in=
dicates a larger IQR (more variability in the central 50% of the data), whe=
reas a shorter box indicates that the central data are more tightly cluster=
ed.</li></ul>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-30e7cda elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"30e7cda" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<ul><li><strong data-start=3D"10105" data-end=3D"10121">Median Lin=
e:</strong> Inside the box, a line is drawn at the median value (Q2). This =
line divides the box into two parts. If the median line is precisely in the=
 middle of the box, it suggests the dataset=E2=80=99s middle is symmetric a=
round the median. If the median is closer to the bottom of the box (closer =
to Q1) or the top of the box (closer to Q3), it indicates skewness in the d=
ata. For example, a median line near Q1 (with an extended upper portion of =
the box) would typically indicate a right-skewed distribution (a longer tai=
l on the high side of the data).</li></ul>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-0c8d70a elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"0c8d70a" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<ul><li><strong data-start=3D"10702" data-end=3D"10715">Whiskers:<=
/strong> The =E2=80=9Cwhiskers=E2=80=9D are the lines that extend from the =
sides of the box out to the minimum and maximum values <strong data-start=
=3D"10821" data-end=3D"10857">that are not considered outliers</strong>. In=
 a standard box plot without any outliers, the whiskers extend to the actua=
l minimum and maximum of the dataset. However, if there are outliers, the w=
hiskers go to the last data points still inside the outlier fences (within =
1.5=C3=97IQR of Q1 and Q3). The ends of the whiskers may be marked with a s=
mall horizontal tick or line to denote the minimum or maximum value at that=
 end. The length of the whiskers can give you a sense of how the data is sp=
read on the lower and upper ends. If one whisker is significantly more prol=
onged than the other, that suggests the distribution has a longer tail on t=
hat side (again, an indication of skewness).</li></ul>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-55b0d16 elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"55b0d16" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<ul><li><strong data-start=3D"11611" data-end=3D"11630">Outlier Po=
ints:</strong> If present, outliers will appear as individual points or sym=
bols that lie beyond the whiskers. Each outlier on the plot corresponds to =
a specific data value that was identified as an outlier. By plotting them, =
the box plot gives a clear visual cue of any anomalies or extreme values in=
 the dataset. No outlier points means all data fell within the 1.5=C3=97IQR=
 bounds from the box.</li></ul>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-c1a1515 elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"c1a1515" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p>The <strong data-start=3D"12059" data-end=3D"12076">scale or ax=
is</strong> on the plot provides context, typically a number line that span=
s from a value slightly below the minimum to one slightly above the maximum=
. This allows you to read off approximate values for Q1, the median, Q3, an=
d so on, directly from the plot itself. For instance, you might see that th=
e median line is around value 50, the box spans roughly 40 to 60, and whisk=
ers go out to about 30 and 85, just by looking at the axes</p>								</div=
>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-1ea62da elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"1ea62da" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p>In summary, the box-and-whisker plot condenses your dataset int=
o a visual summary. <strong data-start=3D"12538" data-end=3D"12633">It high=
lights where the central half of the data lies, the overall spread, and any=
 outliers</strong> at a glance. This makes it an excellent tool for explora=
tory data analysis and for quickly communicating the key characteristics of=
 the data.</p>								</div>
				</div>
				</div>
		<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-20faca53 e-con-full e-f=
lex e-con e-child" data-id=3D"20faca53" data-element_type=3D"container" id=
=3D"characteristics">
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-5e3e990e elementor-wi=
dget elementor-widget-heading" data-id=3D"5e3e990e" data-element_type=3D"wi=
dget" data-widget_type=3D"heading.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
					<span id=3D"elementor-toc__heading-anchor-8" class=3D"elementor-menu-a=
nchor "></span><h2 class=3D"elementor-heading-title elementor-size-default"=
>Key characteristics of a box plot:</h2>				</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-3c38d9de elementor-wi=
dget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"3c38d9de" data-element_type=
=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<ul><li>It <strong data-start=3D"18143" data-end=3D"18166">display=
s the median</strong> (a measure of central tendency) and the <strong data-=
start=3D"18207" data-end=3D"18220">quartiles</strong> (measures of spread) =
without assuming any particular distribution for the data (unlike, for exam=
ple, the mean and standard deviation, which take a normal distribution for =
specific interpretations).</li></ul>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-746f5f83 elementor-wi=
dget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"746f5f83" data-element_type=
=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<ul><li>It <strong data-start=3D"18412" data-end=3D"18435">highlig=
hts outliers</strong> clearly as individual points, which helps detect anom=
alies.</li></ul>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-526ef645 elementor-wi=
dget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"526ef645" data-element_type=
=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<ul><li>It=E2=80=99s also known by other names, such as <strong da=
ta-start=3D"18595" data-end=3D"18622">box-and-whisker diagram</strong>, but=
 all these terms refer to the same type of plot.</li></ul>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-73544eb5 elementor-wi=
dget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"73544eb5" data-element_type=
=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p>Box plots were introduced by the statistician John Tukey as par=
t of exploratory data analysis. Their strength lies in their ability to <st=
rong data-start=3D"18855" data-end=3D"18904">summarise data distribution in=
 a concise form</strong>. For instance, if you have test scores of two diff=
erent classes, two side-by-side box plots can immediately tell you which cl=
ass had a higher median score, which had more variability, and if either cl=
ass had outliers (perhaps a student who performed very differently from the=
 rest).</p>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-3b6aa8aa elementor-wi=
dget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"3b6aa8aa" data-element_type=
=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p>Because a box plot provides a <strong data-start=3D"19220" data=
-end=3D"19245">quick visual snapshot</strong>, it=E2=80=99s beneficial when=
 comparing multiple datasets or when you need to convey the spread of data =
quickly to an audience. Instead of listing all the data points or just prov=
iding one summary statistic, such as the average, a box plot displays <em d=
ata-start=3D"19479" data-end=3D"19485">both</em> the centre and spread, as =
well as outliers. This combination of information is why box plots are wide=
ly used in statistical analysis, quality control, and many scientific field=
s.</p>								</div>
				</div>
				</div>
		<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-5fa4954e e-con-full e-f=
lex e-con e-child" data-id=3D"5fa4954e" data-element_type=3D"container" id=
=3D"use">
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-65d9aa4 elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-heading" data-id=3D"65d9aa4" data-element_type=3D"widg=
et" data-widget_type=3D"heading.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
					<span id=3D"elementor-toc__heading-anchor-9" class=3D"elementor-menu-a=
nchor "></span><h2 class=3D"elementor-heading-title elementor-size-default"=
>When to Use a Box Plot</h2>				</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-581aeb25 elementor-wi=
dget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"581aeb25" data-element_type=
=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p>You may wonder, <em data-start=3D"19710" data-end=3D"19775">=E2=
=80=9CIn what situations is a box plot the appropriate tool to use?=E2=80=
=9D</em> Box plots are especially useful in the following scenarios:</p>			=
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-26da0518 elementor-wi=
dget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"26da0518" data-element_type=
=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<ul><li><strong data-start=3D"19839" data-end=3D"19875">Understand=
ing Data Distribution:</strong> Use a box plot&nbsp;<strong>to&nbsp;<strong=
>visualise the distribution of a numerical dataset quickly</strong>.</stron=
g> It displays the centre, spread, and any skewness or outliers in the data=
. If you have a single dataset and you want to summarise its main features,=
 a box plot is an excellent choice. For example, if you suppose the ages of=
 participants in a survey, a box plot in that plot will show the median age=
, the range, and whether there are any particularly young or old outliers i=
n the group.</li></ul>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-5e858905 elementor-wi=
dget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"5e858905" data-element_type=
=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<ul><li><strong data-start=3D"20406" data-end=3D"20436">Comparing =
Multiple Groups:</strong> If you have multiple datasets (e.g., test scores =
from different classes or heights of plants under different treatments), bo=
x plots enable easy <strong data-start=3D"20585" data-end=3D"20613">side-by=
-side comparisons</strong>. By plotting a box plot for each group on the sa=
me scale, you can compare medians (which group tends to have higher values)=
, the IQRs (which group has more variability), and the presence of outliers=
 in each. This is much cleaner than overlapping histograms or bar charts fo=
r multiple groups. For example, comparing salaries across different departm=
ents of a company using box plots can reveal which department has a higher =
median wage or greater wage variation.</li></ul>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-6e1b4c6b elementor-wi=
dget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"6e1b4c6b" data-element_type=
=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<ul><li><strong data-start=3D"21083" data-end=3D"21106">Detecting =
Outliers:</strong> When your goal is to <strong data-start=3D"21128" data-e=
nd=3D"21149">identify outliers</strong> and understand if your data has lon=
g tails, box plots are convenient. They incorporate the outlier detection r=
ule (1.5 =C3=97 IQR) in the visualisation, making unusual data points stand=
 out. This is useful in preliminary data analysis =E2=80=93 for instance, c=
hecking sensor data for anomalies or examining experimental measurements to=
 identify any runs that produced aberrant results.</li></ul>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-799f770 elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"799f770" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<ul><li><strong data-start=3D"21568" data-end=3D"21600">Non-Parame=
tric Data Summary:</strong> If you do not want to assume a specific statist=
ical distribution (like normal distribution) and you prefer median/quartile=
s over mean/standard deviation (especially in skewed data), box plots are i=
deal. They are based on rank statistics (medians and quartiles), making the=
m more <strong data-start=3D"21880" data-end=3D"21918">robust to skewed dat=
a and outliers</strong> than the an/S and standard deviation. For example, =
income data is often skewed (with a few people earning very high incomes). =
A box plot of incomes would be more informative than a mean and standard de=
viation (SD) because the median and quartiles convey the typical range more=
 effectively, and high earners will appear as outliers, rather than pulling=
 the mean upward.</li></ul>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-14f87581 elementor-wi=
dget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"14f87581" data-element_type=
=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<ul><li><strong data-start=3D"22245" data-end=3D"22272">Compact Re=
presentation:</strong> Box plots offer a <strong data-start=3D"22293" data-=
end=3D"22318">compact visualisation</strong>, particularly useful when work=
ing with numerous datasets or a large dataset. They don=E2=80=99t show ever=
y data point, which can be an advantage when the dataset is large (showing =
every point might be overwhelming or cluttered). Instead, they summarise th=
e data=E2=80=99s most important aspects. For instance, in large-scale data =
analysis or when presenting results to an audience, you might not want to p=
lot thousands of points. A box plot simplifies this by showing just five su=
mmary points and any outliers, giving insight without excessive detail.</li=
></ul>								</div>
				</div>
		<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-970afd8 e-con-full e-fl=
ex e-con e-child" data-id=3D"970afd8" data-element_type=3D"container" id=3D=
"when-not">
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-111d06e elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-heading" data-id=3D"111d06e" data-element_type=3D"widg=
et" data-widget_type=3D"heading.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
					<span id=3D"elementor-toc__heading-anchor-10" class=3D"elementor-menu-=
anchor "></span><h3 class=3D"elementor-heading-title elementor-size-default=
">When not to use a box plot:</h3>				</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-4b13a19 elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"4b13a19" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p>If you need to understand the <em data-start=3D"22914" data-end=
=3D"22924">detailed</em> distribution (for example, the exact shape of the =
distribution, multiple peaks or modes, or any subtle features), a box plot =
may be too simplistic. In such cases, a histogram or density plot might com=
plement the box plot. Additionally, if your dataset is minimal (comprising =
just a handful of points), a box plot may not be very informative; listing =
the points or using a simple bar graph may convey more information in those=
 cases.</p>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-c71e553 elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"c71e553" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p>In summary, use a box plot for a quick and effective visualisat=
ion of distribution when you care about medians, quartiles, and outliers, a=
nd especially when comparing multiple groups. They are commonly used in fie=
lds such as statistics, data science, finance, and any discipline that deal=
s with data analysis because they condense a lot of information into a smal=
l graph. As the Box Plot Calculator is the <strong data-start=3D"23775" dat=
a-end=3D"23789">tool-first</strong> focus here, it enables you to leverage =
these advantages without manually computing anything =E2=80=93 just input y=
our data and interpret the clear output.</p>								</div>
				</div>
				</div>
				</div>
		<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-48089c39 e-con-full e-f=
lex e-con e-child" data-id=3D"48089c39" data-element_type=3D"container" id=
=3D"interpretation">
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-53c03f55 elementor-wi=
dget elementor-widget-heading" data-id=3D"53c03f55" data-element_type=3D"wi=
dget" data-widget_type=3D"heading.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
					<span id=3D"elementor-toc__heading-anchor-11" class=3D"elementor-menu-=
anchor "></span><h2 class=3D"elementor-heading-title elementor-size-default=
">Interpreting the Results</h2>				</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-1ef5f0c0 elementor-wi=
dget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"1ef5f0c0" data-element_type=
=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p>Once you have the five-number summary and the box plot, what ca=
n you learn from them? Here are some tips on <strong data-start=3D"13011" d=
ata-end=3D"13042">how to interpret the output</strong> of the Box Plot Calc=
ulator:</p>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-2505257d elementor-wi=
dget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"2505257d" data-element_type=
=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<ul><li><strong data-start=3D"13074" data-end=3D"13111">Understand=
 the Centre and Spread:</strong> The median (Q2) indicates the central tend=
ency of the data =E2=80=93 half the values are above this number, and half =
are below. Compare the median to the mean (if you happen to know it) to get=
 a sense of skewness; however, even without the mean, the position of the m=
edian line within the box can indicate skew. If the median is not centred i=
n the box, the distribution is skewed. A median toward the lower quartile (=
Q1) means a longer upper tail (right-skewed data), whereas a median toward =
the upper quartile (Q3) means a longer lower tail (left-skewed data).</li><=
/ul>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-6c5fa556 elementor-wi=
dget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"6c5fa556" data-element_type=
=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<ul><li><strong data-start=3D"13665" data-end=3D"13698">Look at th=
e IQR (Box Length):</strong> A larger IQR means more variability in the mid=
dle 50% of your data. If your IQR is very small, it means that many of your=
 data points are clustered closely together around the median. This could i=
ndicate a dataset with very consistent values (low variability) in the cent=
ral range. Conversely, a large IQR indicates the dataset=E2=80=99s middle i=
s more spread out. Remember that the IQR is also used to flag outliers. Add=
itionally, you can compare the IQR to the overall range (max=E2=80=93min) t=
o see how much of the total spread is due to the central bulk of data versu=
s the tails.</li></ul>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-2493418c elementor-wi=
dget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"2493418c" data-element_type=
=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<ul><li><strong data-start=3D"14252" data-end=3D"14280">Compare Wh=
isker Lengths:</strong> The whiskers show the spread of the lower 25% of da=
ta (below Q1) and the upper 25% of data (above Q3). If one whisker is much =
more prolonged than the other, it means the distribution has more spread on=
 that side of the median. For example, a long upper whisker might indicate =
the presence of a few high values that stretch out the scale (even if they=
=E2=80=99re not classified as outliers). This often corresponds to right-sk=
ewness. Similarly, a long lower whisker indicates left-skewness. Ideally (i=
n a perfectly symmetric distribution), the whiskers would be roughly equal =
in length.</li></ul>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-65a30335 elementor-wi=
dget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"65a30335" data-element_type=
=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<ul><li><strong data-start=3D"14851" data-end=3D"14877">Identify A=
ny Outliers:</strong> If the calculator marked outliers, those are values y=
ou should pay attention to. Outliers can <strong data-start=3D"14972" data-=
end=3D"14999">influence your analysis</strong> or indicate exceptional case=
s. Ask yourself: <em data-start=3D"15041" data-end=3D"15133">Are these outl=
ier values mistakes or noise, or do they represent a valid but rare occurre=
nce?</em> For instance, if you=E2=80=99re analysing test scores of a class =
and most are between 50 and 90, but one score is 15, that 15 is an outlier =
that might be a data entry error or a result of a student who missed the te=
st. Outliers aren=E2=80=99t necessarily =E2=80=9Cbad,=E2=80=9D but knowing =
they exist helps you decide how to handle them. In some cases, you might ex=
clude them for specific analyses, or you might investigate them further. Th=
e box plot makes them obvious by isolating them as individual points.</li><=
/ul>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-69ad9bb elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-image" data-id=3D"69ad9bb" data-element_type=3D"widget=
" data-widget_type=3D"image.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
															<img loading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"1024" heig=
ht=3D"415" src=3D"https://boxplotcalculator.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/=
box_plot_outlier-1024x415.webp" class=3D"attachment-large size-large wp-ima=
ge-394" alt=3D"Box plot showing an outlier highlighted beyond the whiskers,=
 detected by the Box Plot Calculator." title=3D"Box Plot Calculator Outlier=
 Detection Example - Box Plot Calculator">															</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-ff05f95 elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"ff05f95" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p style=3D"text-align: center;"><em>Figure 2: Example box plot wi=
th an outlier detected and highlighted by the Box Plot Calculator.</em></p>=
								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-70c411ad elementor-wi=
dget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"70c411ad" data-element_type=
=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<ul><li><strong data-start=3D"15603" data-end=3D"15641">Assess Ove=
rall Distribution Shape:</strong> While a box plot doesn=E2=80=99t show eve=
ry detail of the distribution (for example, it won=E2=80=99t show if the di=
stribution is bimodal =E2=80=94 has two peaks =E2=80=94 since it only uses =
quartiles), it gives a <strong data-start=3D"15824" data-end=3D"15865">high=
-level view of distribution shape</strong>. If the median is precisely in t=
he middle of the box and the whiskers are equal, the distribution is roughl=
y symmetric. If not, you can tell which side is longer (skew). If there are=
 many outliers on one side, that indicates a long tail on that side. The de=
nsity of data within each quartile can also be inferred: if Q1 and the medi=
an are very close together (with a small distance), but the median to Q3 is=
 larger, it suggests that the second quartile of data is tightly packed, wh=
ereas the third quartile is more spread out.</li></ul>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-161f0917 elementor-wi=
dget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"161f0917" data-element_type=
=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p>In practice, use the five-number summary and box plot together.=
 For example, you might report: <em data-start=3D"16466" data-end=3D"16763"=
>=E2=80=9CThe data have a median of 65. The interquartile range is 20 (Q1 =
=3D 50, Q3 =3D 70), with a minimum of 45 and a maximum of 95. The distribut=
ion is slightly right-skewed, as the median is closer to the lower quartile=
, and the upper whisker is longer. Two high outliers were identified (value=
s 90 and 95).=E2=80=9D</em> This kind of interpretation covers centre, spre=
ad, skewness, and outliers, all derived from the box plot output</p>							=
	</div>
				</div>
		<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-a49fa6b e-con-full e-fl=
ex e-con e-child" data-id=3D"a49fa6b" data-element_type=3D"container" id=3D=
"outliers">
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-c89155a elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-heading" data-id=3D"c89155a" data-element_type=3D"widg=
et" data-widget_type=3D"heading.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
					<span id=3D"elementor-toc__heading-anchor-12" class=3D"elementor-menu-=
anchor "></span><h3 class=3D"elementor-heading-title elementor-size-default=
">Outliers in Your Data</h3>				</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-ea8b75c elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"ea8b75c" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p>One of the valuable features of a box plot (and our calculator)=
 is the ability to identify <strong data-start=3D"5557" data-end=3D"5569">o=
utliers</strong>. <strong data-start=3D"5571" data-end=3D"5583">Outliers</s=
trong> are data points that lie far away from the rest of the data =E2=80=
=93 they are unusually high or low values compared to the bulk of observati=
ons. The Box Plot Calculator checks for outliers using the standard <strong=
 data-start=3D"5832" data-end=3D"5850">1.5 * IQR rule</strong>, a common me=
thod in statistics for detecting moderately extreme values.</p>								</di=
v>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-63e76ec elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"63e76ec" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p><strong data-start=3D"6025" data-end=3D"6057">How Outliers Are =
Determined:</strong> After finding Q1, Q3, and the IQR, the calculator comp=
utes =E2=80=9Cfences=E2=80=9D to see if any values fall outside these bound=
s:</p>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-1365470 elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"1365470" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<ul><li>Any data point less than \( Q1 =E2=80=93 1.5 \times \text{=
IQR} \) is considered a low outlier. In other words, it is far below the ma=
in body of data.</li></ul>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-d2d5f74 elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"d2d5f74" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<ul><li>Any data point greater than \( Q3 + 1.5 \times \text{IQR} =
\) is considered a high outlier. It lies far above the rest of the data.</l=
i></ul>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-619ee40 elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"619ee40" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p>Any values outside this range are flagged by the tool as outlie=
rs. For example, if \( Q1 =3D 10 \) and \( Q3 =3D 30 \) (\( IQR =3D 20 \)),=
 then:</p><p>The =E2=80=9Cfence=E2=80=9D for low outliers is:</p><p>\[<br>1=
0 =E2=80=93 1.5(20) =3D 10 =E2=80=93 30 =3D -20<br>\]</p><p>The =E2=80=9Cfe=
nce=E2=80=9D for high outliers is:</p><p>\[<br>30 + 1.5(20) =3D 30 + 30 =3D=
 60<br>\]</p>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-31e5121 elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"31e5121" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p>So any data point below \(-20\) or above \(60\) would be marked=
 as an outlier (in most practical datasets, you won=E2=80=99t have values b=
elow \(-20\) if your data is all positive, but this is just an illustration=
 of the rule).</p>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-39db06d elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"39db06d" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p><strong data-start=3D"7017" data-end=3D"7047">What the Calculat=
or Shows:</strong> If outliers are present, the calculator typically lists =
or highlights them. On the box plot visualisation, <strong data-start=3D"71=
63" data-end=3D"7208">outliers are plotted as individual points</strong> th=
at fall outside the =E2=80=9Cwhiskers=E2=80=9D. This means the whiskers (th=
e lines extending from the box) will stop at the last data point that is no=
t an outlier, and any outlier values will appear as distinct markers (often=
 dots or asterisks) beyond those whisker ends. If your dataset has no outli=
ers by the 1.5*IQR rule, then the whiskers extend to the actual minimum and=
 maximum values of the data.</p>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-58ba29b elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"58ba29b" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p>Identifying outliers is essential. Outliers can <strong data-st=
art=3D"7742" data-end=3D"7764">influence analyses</strong> (for instance, t=
hey can skew the mean significantly) or they might indicate data errors or =
unique cases. By clearly listing outliers, the Box Plot Calculator helps yo=
u spot these values immediately. You can then decide if they are mistakes (=
perhaps a typo in data entry) or true, unusual observations that merit furt=
her investigation. Keep in mind that the 1.5<em data-start=3D"8124" data-en=
d=3D"8216">IQR rule identifies mild outliers (sometimes called =E2=80=9Cout=
side points=E2=80=9D); there is also a 3</em>IQR rule for <em data-start=3D=
"8229" data-end=3D"8247">extreme outliers</em> (very far-out points).=E2=80=
=8BHowever, the calculator focuses on the standard 1.5*IQR cutoff, which is=
 most commonly used for box plots.</p>								</div>
				</div>
				</div>
		<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-c8fc6d4 e-con-full e-fl=
ex e-con e-child" data-id=3D"c8fc6d4" data-element_type=3D"container" id=3D=
"iqr">
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-55d69bd elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-heading" data-id=3D"55d69bd" data-element_type=3D"widg=
et" data-widget_type=3D"heading.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
					<span id=3D"elementor-toc__heading-anchor-13" class=3D"elementor-menu-=
anchor "></span><h3 class=3D"elementor-heading-title elementor-size-default=
">Five-Number Summary &amp; Interquartile Range (IQR)</h3>				</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-af44ee6 elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"af44ee6" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p>When you use the calculator, the primary output you=E2=80=99ll =
see is the <strong data-start=3D"2826" data-end=3D"2849">five-number summar=
y</strong> of your data, along with the <strong data-start=3D"2879" data-en=
d=3D"2908">interquartile range (IQR)</strong>. These are fundamental descri=
ptive statistics that the box plot is based on:</p>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-11d71fd elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"11d71fd" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<ul><li><strong data-start=3D"2989" data-end=3D"3007">Minimum (Min=
):</strong> The smallest data value in your dataset.</li></ul>								</div=
>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-7af3f38 elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"7af3f38" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<ul><li><strong data-start=3D"3095" data-end=3D"3119">First Quarti=
le (Q1):</strong> The lower quartile, or the 25th percentile =E2=80=93 25% =
of the data falls below this value.</li></ul>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-d729197 elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"d729197" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<ul><li><strong data-start=3D"3251" data-end=3D"3267">Median (Q2):=
</strong> The middle value of the dataset (50th percentile) when all number=
s are ordered; half the data points are below this, and half are above.</li=
></ul>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-c94b48c elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"c94b48c" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<ul><li><strong data-start=3D"3451" data-end=3D"3475">Third Quarti=
le (Q3):</strong> The upper quartile, or the 75th percentile =E2=80=93 75% =
of the data falls below this value (and 25% above it).</li></ul>								</d=
iv>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-a6982f7 elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"a6982f7" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<ul><li><strong data-start=3D"3626" data-end=3D"3644">Maximum (Max=
):</strong> The most significant data value in your dataset.</li></ul>					=
			</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-fa6afdc elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-image" data-id=3D"fa6afdc" data-element_type=3D"widget=
" data-widget_type=3D"image.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
															<img loading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"758" heigh=
t=3D"407" src=3D"https://boxplotcalculator.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/s=
unnary-statistics.webp" class=3D"attachment-large size-large wp-image-395" =
alt=3D"Summary statistics panel showing minimum, quartiles, median, maximum=
, mean, IQR, range, sample size, and outlier count." title=3D"Box Plot Calc=
ulator Summary Statistics Output - Box Plot Calculator">															</di=
v>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-06eb10a elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"06eb10a" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p style=3D"text-align: center;"><em>Figure 3: Example summary sta=
tistics output from the Box Plot Calculator, showing minimum, quartiles, me=
dian, maximum, IQR, mean, range, and detected outliers.</em></p>								</d=
iv>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-2ee9ce8 elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"2ee9ce8" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p>These five numbers provide a concise summary of the data=E2=80=
=99s <strong data-start=3D"3789" data-end=3D"3805">distribution. A</strong>=
 box plot is constructed from exactly these five values. From them, you can=
 quickly glean the <strong data-start=3D"4003" data-end=3D"4012">range</str=
ong> (Min to Max), the <strong data-start=3D"4031" data-end=3D"4041">centre=
</strong> (Median), and the <strong data-start=3D"4060" data-end=3D"4070">s=
pread</strong> of the middle 50% of the data (Q1 to Q3).</p>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-07d89a7 elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"07d89a7" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p><strong data-start=3D"4114" data-end=3D"4144">Interquartile Ran=
ge (IQR):</strong> In addition to the five-number summary, the calculator c=
alculates the interquartile range. The <strong data-start=3D"4234" data-end=
=3D"4241">IQR</strong> is simply the difference between the third and first=
 quartiles:</p>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-67fd2ae elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"67fd2ae" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p><span class=3D"katex"><span class=3D"katex-mathml">IQR=3DQ3=E2=
=88=92Q1. </span></span></p>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-92391b7 elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"92391b7" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p>This represents the length of the box in the box plot =E2=80=93=
 it=E2=80=99s the range of the middle half of your data. For example, if Q1=
 =3D 20 and Q3 =3D 30, then IQR =3D 10, meaning the middle 50% of values sp=
an a range of 10 units. The IQR is a valuable measure of statistical disper=
sion, indicating how spread out the central values are. A larger IQR indica=
tes more variability in the middle of the data, while a smaller IQR indicat=
es that the central 50% of the data points are more clustered together.</p>=
								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-e0bc5b1 elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"e0bc5b1" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p>The <strong data-start=3D"4876" data-end=3D"4899">five-number s=
ummary,</strong>&nbsp;together with the <strong data-start=3D"4918" data-en=
d=3D"4925">IQ</strong><strong>,</strong> provides you with&nbsp;a robust sn=
apshot. Extreme values have less influence compared to, say, the mean and s=
tandard deviation. The IQR is often used to help determine <strong data-sta=
rt=3D"5110" data-end=3D"5122">outliers</strong>, which we=E2=80=99ll discus=
s next. By reviewing the min, Q1, median, Q3, and max, you can understand t=
he data=E2=80=99s <strong data-start=3D"5227" data-end=3D"5248">location (m=
edian)</strong>, <strong data-start=3D"5250" data-end=3D"5280">spread (quar=
tiles and IQR)</strong>, and <strong data-start=3D"5286" data-end=3D"5303">=
overall range</strong> =E2=80=93 all of which are immediately computed by t=
he Box Plot Calculator for your convenience.</p>								</div>
				</div>
				</div>
				</div>
		<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-b3d7069 e-con-full e-fl=
ex e-con e-child" data-id=3D"b3d7069" data-element_type=3D"container" id=3D=
"sources">
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-1a8bc30 elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-heading" data-id=3D"1a8bc30" data-element_type=3D"widg=
et" data-widget_type=3D"heading.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
					<span id=3D"elementor-toc__heading-anchor-14" class=3D"elementor-menu-=
anchor "></span><h2 class=3D"elementor-heading-title elementor-size-default=
">Sources</h2>				</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-8a184a4 elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"8a184a4" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<ul><li class=3D"" data-start=3D"34726" data-end=3D"34958"><p clas=
s=3D"" data-start=3D"34729" data-end=3D"34958">Wikipedia, =E2=80=9CFive-num=
ber summary=E2=80=9D =E2=80=93 <em data-start=3D"34764" data-end=3D"34863">=
