		<div role=3D"region" aria-labelledby=3D"e-n-accordion-item-1120" class=3D=
"elementor-element elementor-element-2cb38e50 e-flex e-con-boxed e-con e-ch=
ild" data-id=3D"2cb38e50" data-element_type=3D"container">
					<div class=3D"e-con-inner">
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-14ad7ea5 elementor-wi=
dget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"14ad7ea5" data-element_type=
=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p>The calculator first orders your data from smallest to largest =
(sorting the values). The <strong data-start=3D"24124" data-end=3D"24134">m=
edian</strong> is found as the middle value of the ordered list =E2=80=93 i=
f you have an odd number of data points, it=E2=80=99s the middle one; if yo=
u have an even number of data points, it=E2=80=99s the average of the two m=
iddle values.</p><p>The <strong data-start=3D"24431" data-end=3D"24454">fir=
st quartile (Q1)</strong> is the median of the lower half of the data (belo=
w the median), and the <strong data-start=3D"24527" data-end=3D"24550">thir=
d quartile (Q3)</strong> is the median of the upper half of the data.=E2=80=
=8B For instance, if you have 20 numbers, Q1 is determined by looking at th=
e lowest 10 numbers and taking their median. These quartile values, along w=
ith the min and max, form the five-number summary. (There are slight variat=
ions in quartile calculation methods, but the tool uses a standard method s=
imilar to Tukey=E2=80=99s rule, which is common in statistical software and=
 textbooks.)</p>								</div>
				</div>
					</div>
				</div>
				</div>
					</details>
						<details id=3D"e-n-accordion-item-1121" class=3D"e-n-accordion-item">
				<summary class=3D"e-n-accordion-item-title" data-accordion-index=3D"2" =
tabindex=3D"-1" aria-expanded=3D"false" aria-controls=3D"e-n-accordion-item=
-1121">
					<span class=3D"e-n-accordion-item-title-header"><div class=3D"e-n-acco=
rdion-item-title-text"> How are outliers displayed on the box plot, and are=
 they included in the five-number summary?  </div></span>
							<span class=3D"e-n-accordion-item-title-icon">
			<span class=3D"e-opened"><svg aria-hidden=3D"true" class=3D"e-font-icon-=
svg e-fas-minus" viewBox=3D"0 0 448 512" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/2000/sv=
g"><path d=3D"M416 208H32c-17.67 0-32 14.33-32 32v32c0 17.67 14.33 32 32 32=
h384c17.67 0 32-14.33 32-32v-32c0-17.67-14.33-32-32-32z"></path></svg></spa=
n>
			<span class=3D"e-closed"><svg aria-hidden=3D"true" class=3D"e-font-icon-=
svg e-fas-plus" viewBox=3D"0 0 448 512" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg=
"><path d=3D"M416 208H272V64c0-17.67-14.33-32-32-32h-32c-17.67 0-32 14.33-3=
2 32v144H32c-17.67 0-32 14.33-32 32v32c0 17.67 14.33 32 32 32h144v144c0 17.=
67 14.33 32 32 32h32c17.67 0 32-14.33 32-32V304h144c17.67 0 32-14.33 32-32v=
-32c0-17.67-14.33-32-32-32z"></path></svg></span>
		</span>

						</summary>
				<div role=3D"region" aria-labelledby=3D"e-n-accordion-item-1121" class=
=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-6a8c793e e-con-full e-flex e-con e-=
child" data-id=3D"6a8c793e" data-element_type=3D"container">
		<div role=3D"region" aria-labelledby=3D"e-n-accordion-item-1121" class=3D=
"elementor-element elementor-element-4ec3753d e-flex e-con-boxed e-con e-ch=
ild" data-id=3D"4ec3753d" data-element_type=3D"container">
					<div class=3D"e-con-inner">
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-7bf1aca2 elementor-wi=
dget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"7bf1aca2" data-element_type=
=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p>Outliers are <strong data-start=3D"25194" data-end=3D"25228">di=
splayed as individual points</strong> on the box plot, plotted beyond the w=
hiskers. They are not included within the whiskers =E2=80=93 the whiskers s=
top at the last non-outlier values. In terms of the five-number summary, th=
e <strong data-start=3D"25456" data-end=3D"25479">minimum and maximum</stro=
ng> values are usually the <em data-start=3D"25523" data-end=3D"25567">extr=
emes of the dataset, including outliers</em>. However, when drawing the box=
 plot, if those extremes are outliers, the whiskers will instead end at the=
 nearest values within the outlier cutoff. For clarity, many tools (includi=
ng this calculator) will list identified outliers separately.</p><p>For exa=
mple, you might see output like: Min =3D 5, Q1 =3D 12, Median =3D 20, Q3 =
=3D 28, Max =3D 100, and an outlier noted at 100. In the plot, the upper wh=
isker would perhaps end at a lower value (say 50) if 100 is deemed an outli=
er, and 100 would be plotted as a standalone point. The key idea is that th=
e five-number summary itself <em data-start=3D"26134" data-end=3D"26139">ca=
n</em> include the outlier values as min/max, but the box plot visualisatio=
n marks them separately for better insight. The calculator follows the conv=
ention of showing outliers distinctly so you can immediately spot them.</p>=
								</div>
				</div>
					</div>
				</div>
				</div>
					</details>
						<details id=3D"e-n-accordion-item-1122" class=3D"e-n-accordion-item">
				<summary class=3D"e-n-accordion-item-title" data-accordion-index=3D"3" =
