-1122">
					<span class=3D"e-n-accordion-item-title-header"><div class=3D"e-n-acco=
rdion-item-title-text"> Why do I need at least four data points to create a=
 box plot?  </div></span>
							<span class=3D"e-n-accordion-item-title-icon">
			<span class=3D"e-opened"><svg aria-hidden=3D"true" class=3D"e-font-icon-=
svg e-fas-minus" viewBox=3D"0 0 448 512" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/2000/sv=
g"><path d=3D"M416 208H32c-17.67 0-32 14.33-32 32v32c0 17.67 14.33 32 32 32=
h384c17.67 0 32-14.33 32-32v-32c0-17.67-14.33-32-32-32z"></path></svg></spa=
n>
			<span class=3D"e-closed"><svg aria-hidden=3D"true" class=3D"e-font-icon-=
svg e-fas-plus" viewBox=3D"0 0 448 512" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg=
"><path d=3D"M416 208H272V64c0-17.67-14.33-32-32-32h-32c-17.67 0-32 14.33-3=
2 32v144H32c-17.67 0-32 14.33-32 32v32c0 17.67 14.33 32 32 32h144v144c0 17.=
67 14.33 32 32 32h32c17.67 0 32-14.33 32-32V304h144c17.67 0 32-14.33 32-32v=
-32c0-17.67-14.33-32-32-32z"></path></svg></span>
		</span>

						</summary>
				<div role=3D"region" aria-labelledby=3D"e-n-accordion-item-1122" class=
=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-640300c0 e-con-full e-flex e-con e-=
child" data-id=3D"640300c0" data-element_type=3D"container">
		<div role=3D"region" aria-labelledby=3D"e-n-accordion-item-1122" class=3D=
"elementor-element elementor-element-78c25791 e-flex e-con-boxed e-con e-ch=
ild" data-id=3D"78c25791" data-element_type=3D"container">
					<div class=3D"e-con-inner">
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-58b957a5 elementor-wi=
dget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"58b957a5" data-element_type=
=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p>By definition, to compute quartiles (Q1 and Q3) and a median, y=
ou need a dataset that can be divided into quarters. With too few data poin=
ts, these statistics become ill-defined or not very informative. For exampl=
e, with 3 data points, you have a median, but essentially each =E2=80=9Cqua=
rtile=E2=80=9D would be an endpoint =E2=80=94 there isn=E2=80=99t a real =
=E2=80=9Cmiddle half=E2=80=9D of the data to form a box.</p><p>Most box plo=
t tools (including this one) require a minimum of 4 data points=E2=80=8B to=
 ensure a meaningful median and at least one data point in each half, there=
by determining Q1 and Q3. With 4 points, the median is the average of the m=
iddle two, and Q1 is the first data point (median of the lower two), and Q3=
 is the fourth data point (median of the upper two). That=E2=80=99s just en=
ough to draw a rudimentary box plot. With fewer than 4, it=E2=80=99s better=
 to look at the raw values directly.</p><p>In short, at least four values e=
nsure the calculations behind the box plot make sense and the plot can be d=
rawn properly.</p>								</div>
				</div>
					</div>
				</div>
				</div>
					</details>
