		<div role=3D"region" aria-labelledby=3D"e-n-accordion-item-1123" class=3D=
"elementor-element elementor-element-77ebcc24 e-flex e-con-boxed e-con e-ch=
ild" data-id=3D"77ebcc24" data-element_type=3D"container">
					<div class=3D"e-con-inner">
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-4af2af95 elementor-wi=
dget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"4af2af95" data-element_type=
=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p><strong data-start=3D"27599" data-end=3D"27607">Yes.</strong> T=
he Box Plot Calculator works for any set of real numbers, whether they are =
positive, negative, whole numbers, or decimals. You might be analysing temp=
eratures (which could be below zero), financial data (profits and losses), =
or scientific measurements with decimals =E2=80=93 all of these are fine. J=
ust input them like any other numbers.</p><p>The calculations for quartiles=
, median, and outliers are the same regardless of the numeric values=E2=80=
=99 sign or whether they are integers or not. For example, you could input =
<code data-start=3D"28111" data-end=3D"28133">-5, -1.2, 0, 3.8, 10</code> a=
nd you would get a five-number summary (min =3D -5, Q1 =3D -1.2, median =3D=
 0, Q3 =3D 3.8, max =3D 10) and a box plot spanning negative to positive va=
lues. The number line on the plot will adjust accordingly to accommodate th=
e range of your data. Just ensure you separate the numbers with commas or s=
paces as usual, and the tool will handle the rest.</p>								</div>
				</div>
					</div>
