t=3D"28726" data-end=3D"28755">shape of the distribution</strong> =E2=80=93=
 you can see if the data is bell-shaped, skewed, has multiple peaks (bimoda=
l), etc., by looking at how the bars are arranged. It plots the frequency o=
f data points in continuous value intervals (bins). However, it doesn=E2=80=
=99t give specific summary statistics easily, and identifying quartiles or =
medians from a histogram can be imprecise without further calculation.</p><=
/li><li class=3D"" data-start=3D"29121" data-end=3D"29731"><p class=3D"" da=
ta-start=3D"29123" data-end=3D"29731">A <strong data-start=3D"29125" data-e=
nd=3D"29137">box plot</strong> provides a <strong data-start=3D"29149" data=
-end=3D"29165">summary view</strong> focusing on medians and quartiles. It =
doesn=E2=80=99t show detailed shape (for example, you can=E2=80=99t tell if=
 the distribution is bimodal from a box plot alone), but it very clearly&nb=
sp;<strong data-start=3D"29392" data-end=3D"29424"><span style=3D"box-sizin=
g: border-box;">indicates the&nbsp;<strong>centre</strong></span>, spread, =
and outliers</strong>. One significant advantage is that box plots make it =
easy to compare multiple distributions side by side without clutter; wherea=
s comparing multiple histograms can be messy or require separate panels, mu=
ltiple box plots can be drawn on one chart for direct comparison.</p></li><=
/ul><p class=3D"" data-start=3D"29733" data-end=3D"30378">In practice, thes=
e two plots complement each other. If you have the luxury of examining both=
, a histogram can tell you about things like modality or subtle distributio=
n shapes. At the same time, a box plot will succinctly summarise the key st=
atistics and outliers. For a quick summary (especially in reports or when y=
ou have many datasets to compare), box plots are often preferred due to the=
ir clarity and compactness. The Box Plot Calculator focuses on generating t=
he box plot and summary,. Still, youcould use the summary it provides to in=
form other analyses (including making a histogram separately if needed).</p=
